<h2>The Question</h2>
<p>
    "What standard do we have around navigation?" The
    <a href="/intents/navigation/">Navigation Intent</a> carried a single dimension —
    <code>structure</code> = <code>hierarchical</code> | <code>lateral</code> | <code>linear</code> —
    making it the thinnest intent in the catalog. Its siblings carry five or six axes
    (<a href="/intents/modal/">modal</a> 5, <a href="/intents/anchor/">anchor</a> 6,
    <a href="/intents/loader/">loader</a> 5, <a href="/intents/validation/">validation</a> 5).
    Meanwhile the <a href="/blocks/router/">Router block</a> already shipped <code>scroll</code>,
    <code>transition</code>, <code>route:guard:leave</code>, and Navigation-API history control.
</p>
<p>
    The intent <strong>under-described its own implementation</strong>: a Tabs (<code>lateral</code>)
    or Wizard (<code>linear</code>) block could declare its information-architecture shape but had
    no vocabulary to declare scroll behavior, history contribution, transition direction, or
    leave-guarding. The question this research answers: which other separable navigation-UX
    concerns deserve to be first-class dimensions, and which belong elsewhere?
</p>

<h2>The Intent Bar</h2>
<p>
    A candidate concern earns a dimension only if it is all four of: (a) <strong>user-perceivable
    behavior</strong>, (b) a <strong>real choice with 2–4 named values</strong>, (c)
    <strong>orthogonal</strong> to <code>structure</code>, and (d) grounded in a <strong>web
    platform standard</strong> or a strong cross-framework convention. Held to that bar, of eight
    candidates investigated, four became dimensions, one was added with weaker grounding, two
    deferred to neighbouring intents, and the rest were classed implementation detail.
</p>

<h2>The Five Dimensions</h2>
<table>
    <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Values</th><th>What the user perceives</th><th>Grounding</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td><code>structure</code> <em>(kept)</em></td>
        <td>hierarchical · lateral · linear</td>
        <td>The IA model: back-stack vs peer tabs vs locked wizard</td>
        <td>Information-architecture convention</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><code>history</code></td>
        <td>push · replace · none</td>
        <td>What the browser Back button does after this navigation</td>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Navigation/navigate">Navigation API <code>navigate({history})</code></a></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><code>scroll</code></td>
        <td>auto · top · preserve · manual</td>
        <td>Where the viewport lands after the view swaps</td>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/NavigateEvent/intercept"><code>intercept({scroll})</code></a> + <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/History/scrollRestoration"><code>scrollRestoration</code></a></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><code>transition</code></td>
        <td>directional · fade · none</td>
        <td>Whether forward slides forward and Back slides back</td>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/View_Transition_API">View Transitions API</a> + transition types</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><code>guard</code></td>
        <td>free · confirm · blocked</td>
        <td>Whether leaving can be interrupted (unsaved changes)</td>
        <td>Navigation <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/NavigateEvent/intercept"><code>intercept</code></a> + <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/beforeunload_event"><code>beforeunload</code></a></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><code>persistence</code></td>
        <td>url · memory · session</td>
        <td>Whether this view state is bookmarkable / shareable</td>
        <td>WHATWG URL vs <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/History_API/Working_with_the_History_API">History <code>state</code></a> split</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<h3>Why each one clears the bar</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong><code>history</code> — the textbook fit.</strong> <code>navigate(url, { history:
        "auto" | "push" | "replace" })</code> is a named platform enum that directly determines
        what the Back button does. <code>none</code> covers transient view changes that should
        not enter the back stack at all.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong><code>scroll</code> — the platform's binary knob, refined for users.</strong> The
        API exposes only <code>scroll: "after-transition" | "manual"</code> and
        <code>scrollRestoration: "auto" | "manual"</code>. The user-facing refinement of "what
        manual does" is <code>top</code> vs <code>preserve</code> — exactly the abstraction an
        intent adds over the raw API. React Router's <code>&lt;ScrollRestoration&gt;</code> exists
        because the SPA default isn't enough; the choice is real.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong><code>transition</code> — directionality has no other home.</strong>
        Browser-initiated Back navigations (back button, edge-swipe) carry <strong>no</strong>
        View-Transition type, so directional animation must be <em>derived from</em>
        history-traversal direction. The <a href="/intents/motion/">motion intent</a> owns
        <em>feel</em> (<code>physics: natural|immediate|reduced</code>, honoring
        <code>prefers-reduced-motion</code>); it structurally cannot know a navigation is
        "forward." So <code>transition</code> owns <em>direction only</em> and defers timing and
        easing to <code>motion</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong><code>guard</code> — doubly grounded.</strong> "Can the user be stopped before
        leaving" is standardized on <em>both</em> the Navigation API (<code>navigate</code> event
        <code>canIntercept</code> + <code>preventDefault</code>/<code>intercept</code>) and
        <code>beforeunload</code> (cross-document / tab-close). Cross-framework convergence (React
        Router <code>useBlocker</code>, Vue <code>beforeRouteLeave</code>) corroborates. The in-app
        "unsaved changes" prompt composes with <a href="/intents/modal/">modal</a>.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong><code>persistence</code> — the deep-linkability choice.</strong> Most relevant
        exactly where <code>structure</code> is <code>lateral</code> (is the active tab in the
        URL?) or <code>linear</code> (is the wizard step shareable?). <code>url</code> lives in
        path/search and survives refresh and share; <code>session</code> rides History
        <code>state</code> and survives traversal but not a fresh share; <code>memory</code> is
        in-memory only. This is the <strong>weakest grounding</strong> of the five — a
        URL-vs-<code>state</code> convention rather than a single enum — and is flagged as an open
        point.
    </li>
</ul>

<h2>Composition Boundary — What Navigation Does NOT Own</h2>
<table>
    <tr><th>Concern</th><th>Verdict</th><th>Why</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Prefetch eagerness</td>
        <td>→ <a href="/intents/prefetch/">prefetch intent</a></td>
        <td><code>eagerness: viewport|hover|interaction</code> already owns it; navigation composes, doesn't duplicate.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Animation feel (spring / instant / reduced)</td>
        <td>→ <a href="/intents/motion/">motion intent</a></td>
        <td><code>motion.physics</code> owns feel; <code>navigation.transition</code> owns direction only.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Focus-on-route-change</td>
        <td>reference, don't own</td>
        <td>The correct answer is opinionated (WAI-ARIA APG: move to the new view's main heading) and overlaps <a href="/intents/focus-delegation/">focus-delegation</a>. Navigation cites the <code>focusReset</code> contract; the closed value set stays with a focus-owning intent.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><code>aria-current</code> (page / step / location)</td>
        <td>derived, not a dimension</td>
        <td><code>page</code> for hierarchical/lateral, <code>step</code> for linear — a <em>function of</em> <code>structure</code>, so it fails orthogonality. The structure contract specifies the mapping.</td>
    </tr>
</table>
<p>
    Classed <strong>implementation/config, not UX preference</strong> (kept out entirely): nested
    / parallel routing, base path, hash-vs-history router mode, deep-link 404 fallback,
    cross-document-vs-same-document execution mode, and lazy view loading (eagerness →
    <code>prefetch</code>, pending-state UX → <code>loader</code>).
</p>

<h2>Web Standards Alignment</h2>
<table>
    <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How It Grounds a Dimension</th></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Navigation/navigate">Navigation API <code>navigate()</code></a></td><td>Baseline 2024</td><td><code>history</code> (push/replace), <code>guard</code> (intercept/preventDefault)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/NavigateEvent/intercept"><code>NavigateEvent.intercept()</code></a></td><td>Baseline 2024</td><td><code>scroll</code> (<code>scroll: after-transition|manual</code>), focus (<code>focusReset</code>, referenced)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/History/scrollRestoration"><code>History.scrollRestoration</code></a></td><td>Baseline</td><td><code>scroll</code> auto/manual base</td></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/View_Transition_API">View Transitions API</a></td><td>Baseline 2024 (same-doc)</td><td><code>transition</code> directionality via transition types</td></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/beforeunload_event"><code>beforeunload</code></a></td><td>Legacy / wide support</td><td><code>guard</code> for cross-document & tab-close</td></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/History_API/Working_with_the_History_API">History <code>state</code></a> vs URL</td><td>Baseline</td><td><code>persistence</code> url/session/memory split</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>The Intent Was Lagging the Block</h2>
<p>
    Every added dimension maps 1:1 to a Router attribute that already exists — documenting the
    vocabulary closes a <a href="/research/">design-first</a> gap, it does not request new
    implementation:
</p>
<table>
    <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Existing Router surface</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>scroll</code></td><td><code>&lt;route-view scroll="auto|manual|none"&gt;</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>transition</code></td><td><code>&lt;route-view transition&gt;</code> + View Transitions integration</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>guard</code></td><td><code>route:guard:leave</code> (exit guard)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>history</code></td><td>Navigation API <code>history</code> option in <code>navigate(path, options)</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>persistence</code></td><td>URLPattern params/query vs in-memory route state</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Open Points</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>persistence grounding</strong> 🔶 — confirm <code>url | memory | session</code> or collapse to <code>url | memory</code>; the three-way set rests on convention, not a single enum.</li>
    <li><strong>transition vs motion</strong> ⚠ — keep the boundary clean: <code>navigation.transition</code> = direction, <code>motion.physics</code> = feel.</li>
    <li><strong>focus-reset home</strong> 🔶 — decide whether <code>heading | target | preserve | auto</code> becomes an axis on <a href="/intents/focus-delegation/">focus-delegation</a> or stays an APG-cited prose contract.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    These are tracked in the backlog (<code>backlog/057-nav-persistence-grounding.md</code>,
    <code>backlog/058-nav-transition-vs-motion.md</code>, <code>backlog/056-nav-focus-reset-home.md</code>)
    and the companion report <code>reports/2026-06-03-navigation-intent-vocabulary.md</code>.
</p>

